WEBVTT

00:00.930 --> 00:02.112
Amen, please be seated.

00:13.588 --> 00:25.586
This morning, we have a psalm before us that points our focus as God's people to God in the face of trouble.

00:27.042 --> 00:34.870
What we have here in Psalm 20 is what we call a royal psalm, which would have been offered as something of a prayer for the king.

00:34.910 --> 00:44.679
And yet, we see ultimately that this psalm roots the believer's faith, not in someone like David, but in the Lord himself.

00:45.620 --> 00:55.890
In fact, we're gonna see from this passage that the psalm is ultimately about Jesus, our God who is king, the one in whom we place

00:56.450 --> 00:57.131
our faith.

00:58.032 --> 01:02.757
But as we consider Psalm 20 this morning, when I asked the question, what is its theme?

01:03.738 --> 01:07.762
Well, quite simply, the theme of Psalm 20 is trust.

01:09.644 --> 01:13.609
Psalm 20 offers a unique perspective of the believer's trust in the Lord.

01:13.669 --> 01:26.002
It considers our assurance as believers to face whatever may come with full confidence that the Lord, He is sovereign, that He is mighty and powerful to save.

01:26.498 --> 01:29.701
and that he is really near to his people.

01:29.762 --> 01:32.024
He is really near to you.

01:32.044 --> 01:39.953
And the mindset of the psalmist is one that expects trouble and knows that danger lurks.

01:39.993 --> 01:44.297
The author is not deluded or misinformed regarding what threats lay before him.

01:45.459 --> 01:55.890
And so church, let us this morning hear God's word and be so strengthened in our trust in the Lord that we can meet today and that we can meet tomorrow

01:56.514 --> 02:00.800
with full confidence because God is your God.

02:02.802 --> 02:05.085
Before we read God's word, would you pray with me?

02:05.145 --> 02:05.786
Let's pray together.

02:08.029 --> 02:13.857
Oh God, we thank you that you have spoken, or that you have revealed Christ to us in your word.

02:13.957 --> 02:17.301
Every page of our Bibles is about Jesus.

02:18.944 --> 02:23.890
And Father, we ask that you would exalt Him in our hearts, in our minds, that we

02:24.194 --> 02:29.242
would bow before him who rules and who reigns, even now, all authority and dominion has been given to him.

02:30.644 --> 02:37.494
And so would we pray that your word to us might be as sweet, as honey, and as valuable as gold.

02:38.716 --> 02:47.089
Might you instruct us, might you teach us, might you whittle our hearts, O Lord, that we might be formed in fashion more and more into the image of Christ.

02:48.451 --> 02:53.298
And so Father, we pray that you would give us ears to hear, and hearts to love, and eyes to see,

02:53.570 --> 02:58.057
hands to work, a mind to know, a will to desire.

02:58.257 --> 03:01.242
Oh Lord, affections for you.

03:01.262 --> 03:03.245
You pray and ask these things in Jesus' name.

03:03.906 --> 03:04.207
Amen.

03:05.449 --> 03:07.191
This is Psalm chapter 20.

03:07.251 --> 03:08.233
This is God's Word.

03:08.794 --> 03:09.214
Perfect.

03:10.216 --> 03:10.817
Let us give you here.

03:13.341 --> 03:17.427
To the choir master, a psalm of David.

03:19.130 --> 03:21.714
May the Lord answer you in the day of trouble

03:22.562 --> 03:25.286
May the name of the God of Jacob protect you.

03:26.609 --> 03:31.937
May he send you help from the sanctuary and give you support from Zion.

03:32.979 --> 03:38.328
May he remember all your offerings in regard with favor your burnt sacrifices.

03:39.690 --> 03:40.191
Say la.

03:43.196 --> 03:46.802
May he grant you your heart's desire and fulfill all your plans.

03:47.362 --> 03:52.628
May we shout for joy over your salvation and in the name of our God, set up our banners.

03:53.649 --> 03:55.792
May the Lord fulfill all your petitions.

03:57.293 --> 03:59.416
Now I know that the Lord saves his anointed.

04:00.056 --> 04:04.081
He will answer him from his holy heaven with the saving might of his right hand.

04:04.942 --> 04:13.051
Some trust in chariots and some in horses, but we trust in the name of the Lord our God.

04:14.173 --> 04:15.474
They collapse in fall.

04:16.194 --> 04:17.996
but we rise and stand upright.

04:18.897 --> 04:20.319
O Lord, save the king.

04:21.321 --> 04:23.824
May he answer us when we call.

04:25.366 --> 04:27.108
Amen.

04:27.128 --> 04:29.651
The grass withers and the flower fades.

04:30.352 --> 04:33.156
The word of our God stands forever and ever.

04:33.937 --> 04:35.579
Thanks be to God.

04:39.684 --> 04:44.050
As most of you know that I am a transplant here to Northwest Arkansas,

04:44.962 --> 04:51.671
And one of the things I left behind in South Carolina is I've traded hurricanes for tornadoes.

04:53.574 --> 05:14.322
I want you to correct me after the service as I'm kind of assuming some things here, but I imagine that being in, is it in our cans and being landlocked means that when June 1 comes around, you don't start fretting about the systems churning in the Atlantic or in the Gulf or whatever's coming off the coast of Africa.

05:15.682 --> 05:23.792
And yet in South Carolina over the summers, we would all begin paying a little more attention to our beloved local meteorologist, Ed Pietrowski.

05:24.373 --> 05:25.594
And we will do so closely.

05:26.695 --> 05:40.753
Because when he reports that there's a disturbance being monitored in the Atlantic, and as he crunches numbers and he shares spaghetti graphs, we not only watch and wait, but we also prepare.

05:42.234 --> 05:45.138
We go to the store and we buy all of our essentials.

05:45.378 --> 05:48.162
Make sure our generators are gassed up.

05:48.242 --> 05:51.467
We go and we get sandbags after sandbags.

05:51.507 --> 05:53.070
We stalk our pantries.

05:53.110 --> 05:54.752
We buy flashlights and batteries.

05:54.792 --> 05:55.914
We check on our neighbors.

05:55.994 --> 06:01.122
We batten down the hatches and we put plywood over our windows.

06:02.424 --> 06:11.258
And yet when the winds pick up and the clouds roll in and the storms begin, well, what are we to do?

06:11.278 --> 06:14.162
For surely our preparation means little.

06:14.754 --> 06:27.030
Should we not have prayed to the one who parted the waters, to the one who calmed the storm, to the one who sent floods and covered the earth with the depths, and the one who promised never to flood the earth again?

06:27.070 --> 06:32.638
You see, preparation without prayer is folly.

06:34.380 --> 06:39.767
And similarly, this psalm sets God's people on the brink of uncertainty.

06:39.807 --> 06:41.810
The clouds are gathering.

06:42.274 --> 06:47.722
There's the potential in the proverbial storm rolling in and surely they'll prepare for wars.

06:47.742 --> 06:52.510
There's likely a note here that these troubles mentioned are likely wars or battle.

06:53.491 --> 06:59.941
But the highest calling for the Israelite and for the Christian is to seek the Lord and to pray.

07:01.003 --> 07:10.738
Whether storms or war or global pandemics or economic uncertainty or political upheaval or even grief and loss

07:11.202 --> 07:22.619
or hardship, whatever it may be, the theme of this Psalm reminds us that when trouble is on the horizon, yes, we should plan, yes, we should prepare, but above all, we should pray.

07:22.639 --> 07:40.626
And so this morning, we're going to look at really one major point about such prayer, that for the Christian, when we pray, we really cry unto the Lord, considering the Christians cry this morning.

07:41.890 --> 07:45.053
It is somewhat ironic that our Psalm considers preparations for battle.

07:45.634 --> 07:48.737
For surely men were mustered and organized and inspected.

07:48.797 --> 07:56.425
They were distributed and plans were prepared, but the words in tone of the Psalm reflect the pinnacle of preparation for battle.

07:57.226 --> 07:59.808
But the king and his people should seek the Lord.

08:01.190 --> 08:02.891
And there's a fair question here, I think.

08:02.932 --> 08:09.298
What good is prayer as a means of preparation for something like war?

08:10.722 --> 08:22.943
Surely this is the world's mindset and just not just those nations who surrounded Israel, trusting the might and number of men or the power and prowess of their king, but it's the world's mindset today.

08:23.003 --> 08:26.289
What good is prayer?

08:28.112 --> 08:31.698
Well, the theme of this song brings to mind Paul's words in 1 Corinthians.

08:32.546 --> 08:35.810
Paul writes, but God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise.

08:36.230 --> 08:38.332
God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong.

08:38.713 --> 08:50.325
God chose what is low and despised in the world, even things that are not to bring to nothing things that are, so that no human being might boast in the presence of God.

08:51.887 --> 08:55.631
And I don't want you to miss that which is so plain and rooted in this psalm.

08:55.932 --> 09:01.778
It is a deep humility and acknowledgement of the weakness of all men, even kings,

09:01.954 --> 09:04.677
apart from the mercy and help of God.

09:05.938 --> 09:14.366
You know, why is it that we think we can take on each day and stare down the forces of evil and meeting each trial and trouble like Wyatt Earp at the OK Corral?

09:16.388 --> 09:31.122
Most likely that answer is really a deep-seated pride, a sense of self-reliance, which ultimately, whether are expressed intent or not, sounds something like, I don't need you, God, I'm just fine.

09:31.458 --> 09:32.019
without you.

09:33.541 --> 09:46.761
And so we see the orientation of the believer's heart is towards the Lord in prayer because if the king can do nothing apart from the Lord's help, if the king can do nothing apart from the Lord's help, we'll believe it neither can you or myself.

09:48.644 --> 09:58.258
And this weakness serves as a purpose, as Paul's right, as Paul writes, so that no human being might boast in the presence of God, that it might be God who receives all the glory and all the praise.

09:58.899 --> 10:00.722
And it is here that we see our object

10:01.026 --> 10:06.972
of worship, the one to whom we pray, the one to whom we cry out is the very king of the universe.

10:08.034 --> 10:13.379
And when we face uncertainty or stare trouble in the face, might we remember these petitions before the Lord?

10:14.160 --> 10:17.524
And might they inform the language of our prayers?

10:19.726 --> 10:21.188
For first, we find this passage.

10:22.249 --> 10:25.793
The believer cries out, Lord, protect me.

10:27.114 --> 10:30.578
The believer first cries out, Lord, protect me.

10:31.042 --> 10:34.187
In verse 1, there is a call for the Lord to answer you in the day of trouble.

10:34.467 --> 10:37.311
May the name of the God of Jacob protect you.

10:38.493 --> 10:44.642
And again, I want to note the acknowledgment of the people and the king that it is God alone who protects his people.

10:45.683 --> 10:51.152
But isn't it kind of strange that they appeal to the name of the Lord?

10:52.253 --> 10:55.438
Well, what good is a name?

10:56.840 --> 10:58.322
Well, maybe you're a long time

10:58.690 --> 11:02.034
Siloam Springs resident.

11:02.054 --> 11:07.540
Maybe you've been pulled over a time or two, maybe going just a little bit over the speed limit.

11:07.560 --> 11:12.085
You know that a name sometimes can get you out of a speeding ticket.

11:13.467 --> 11:14.848
Maybe it can get you a special rate.

11:16.430 --> 11:21.416
Maybe it can get you expedited service or access to something exclusive.

11:21.516 --> 11:27.122
It can even earn you trust or respect with those that don't know you when you have a name.

11:28.386 --> 11:38.499
We recognize that with some names, there is associated some sense of power or prestige, maybe from their status and society, maybe from their job, or maybe from their reputation.

11:38.859 --> 11:43.825
But what David has in mind, he reflects an ancient Hebrew understanding of what's in a name.

11:45.127 --> 11:51.134
For David and his people, a name spoke to the very being, the very character and trustworthiness of an individual.

11:52.236 --> 11:54.098
It was the Lord's name,

11:54.402 --> 11:59.829
that was given to Moses at the burning bush when he asked, well, who am I to tell the Israelites sent me?

12:01.051 --> 12:02.553
Do you remember what God's response was?

12:02.613 --> 12:04.716
I am who I am.

12:04.776 --> 12:06.579
This is what you were to say to the Israelites.

12:06.879 --> 12:09.663
I am has sent me to you.

12:10.885 --> 12:20.658
This is the name of God which reveals to us Yahweh, or the small capitalized letters, Lord, and the Old Testament referring to the covenant name of God.

12:21.346 --> 12:29.817
It carries with it covenant maker and covenant keeper, steadfast love, holiness, care and compassion among many other qualities.

12:30.999 --> 12:35.464
But at its core, it is this, at least a promise.

12:36.726 --> 12:43.295
For when we cry out to the Lord, he says, in his name, I have been and will always be with you.

12:43.435 --> 12:45.938
I will be your God and you will be my people.

12:47.042 --> 12:49.385
See, this is the God to which you and I pray.

12:49.485 --> 12:56.633
In the very reason we pray with such assurance, with such urgency and trust that the Lord who protected Jacob and his family will protect us.

12:58.074 --> 13:04.441
When we call upon the name of the Lord to protect us, we're calling upon everything that God is to fight for us and to defend us.

13:05.623 --> 13:10.028
And as Proverbs 18 reminds us, the name of the Lord is a strong tower.

13:11.089 --> 13:15.634
The righteous man runs into it and is safe.

13:19.522 --> 13:22.766
I wonder if you've ever been camping in a thunderstorm.

13:24.448 --> 13:36.081
And I don't mean necessarily in an RV or in a trailer, but I mean on the ground, in a tent, in the middle of the woods, or top of mountain, in a torrential downpour with lightning crashing all around.

13:38.183 --> 13:41.226
You know, growing up storms seem to follow us everywhere we set up a tent.

13:44.310 --> 13:48.114
But you're never more aware of just how insufficient of a shelter a tent is

13:48.962 --> 13:52.466
until a small mountain squall pops up in the middle of the night.

13:53.827 --> 14:04.879
But unlike the feeble mesh and tarp of a tent, that the name of the Lord is a strong tower where those who love and cherish his law and word find safety from the onslaught of this world.

14:06.161 --> 14:07.462
Beloved, he is sufficient.

14:07.522 --> 14:09.024
He is a strong tower.

14:09.684 --> 14:15.971
And when troubles arise, when we encounter uncertainties or when enemies set themselves against Christ and his church, where do we turn?

14:16.712 --> 14:17.293
What do we do?

14:17.353 --> 14:18.674
Will we cry out to the Lord?

14:19.234 --> 14:21.737
and pray in the full confidence in the name of God.

14:21.937 --> 14:25.462
We cry out, Lord, protect me."

14:25.482 --> 14:32.130
Second, what I want you to see this morning is that we cry out, the Christians cry, is Lord, be with me, right?

14:32.150 --> 14:34.533
Lord, protect me, Lord, be with me.

14:34.573 --> 14:43.043
And the people in Psalm 20 appeal to the sanctuary and to Zion, which for ancient Israelites was the site where God promised to dwell with His people.

14:43.844 --> 14:45.106
It was the place of worship

14:45.666 --> 14:50.751
It's there that God dwelled and there that the king would have made sacrifices to which the people appeal to in verse three.

14:51.652 --> 15:06.848
The tabernacle also served as a constant reminder that the all surpassing glory of God, the one who is transcendent and the one who is invisible is also near that he resided among his people.

15:06.908 --> 15:12.914
And beloved, he continues to reside among us by the Holy Spirit and Christ.

15:15.586 --> 15:25.395
That's what makes Ezekiel's prophecy of the Lord's departure, leaving the temple all the more terrifying of an account, for if it's the Lord leaving the midst of his people.

15:25.656 --> 15:32.322
So David Psalm and the prayer of the people served as a reminder that help was not only certain, but it was also near.

15:35.025 --> 15:44.914
Our kids have recently enjoyed, I think I maybe have shared this before, I've enjoyed the neighborhood privilege of going out, riding their bikes, and playing with their friends.

15:45.986 --> 15:51.394
What's always sweet is we send them off every time they go armed with a walkie-talkie, okay?

15:53.698 --> 15:58.405
And whenever we send them out, we know that they have access to us, that we are near.

15:58.505 --> 16:00.628
We're never that far away.

16:02.871 --> 16:15.250
Even if they were outside, we know that if they were the fall or if they were to get hurt, we know that they could cry out and we would hear them and we could rush to them and take them up and help them or take them to find the care that they need.

16:16.162 --> 16:16.763
I mean, do you remember?

16:16.803 --> 16:17.385
Have you been there?

16:17.445 --> 16:19.630
You've heard your children outside and you hear the cries.

16:19.950 --> 16:21.213
You know that all cries aren't the same.

16:21.554 --> 16:23.398
You hear that cry and you know something's wrong.

16:24.380 --> 16:30.634
What a blessing it is to know that you're near, that you can come running, that you can scoop them up in your arms and take care of them.

16:30.674 --> 16:34.322
And so church, we have a great assurance here in this passage.

16:34.562 --> 16:36.966
of the proximity to God to His people.

16:37.006 --> 16:41.312
For God here in this Psalm, He dwells in His sanctuary made with hands.

16:41.352 --> 16:46.419
But John informs us in His gospel that the Word became flesh and dwelt among us.

16:46.780 --> 16:51.547
And we have seen His glory, glory as of the only Son from the Father, full of grace and truth.

16:52.428 --> 16:59.058
And when Jesus told the disciples that He was leaving them, He promised them a coming helper, the Holy Spirit.

16:59.426 --> 17:05.513
And again, Jesus is ever so close to you and me by His Spirit, which is the bond that unites us to Christ.

17:06.995 --> 17:12.481
And if the Lord's presence was a comfort and confidence to the King, then surely it is for you and for me.

17:13.442 --> 17:26.898
That appointed appearance of God ushered in the ministry of Jesus' life and death and resurrection and showed to be the grandest of rescues for by Jesus' work, were we not spared from our earthly enemies?

17:29.186 --> 17:30.948
from the grand cosmic enemy of death.

17:32.491 --> 17:39.160
Here with Paul say, where O death is thy victory, where O death is thy sting, the sting of death is sin, and the power of sin is the law.

17:39.700 --> 17:44.327
But thanks be to God, he gives us victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.

17:46.310 --> 17:52.498
Or as Charles Persian puts it, men of the world despise sanctuary help.

17:54.210 --> 17:59.056
But our hearts, believer's hearts, have learned to prize it beyond all material aid.

18:00.478 --> 18:05.484
They seek help out of the armory, or the treasury, or the buttery.

18:06.866 --> 18:09.229
But we turn to the sanctuary.

18:10.651 --> 18:17.459
And as such, we cry out, Lord, be with me, and beloved He is, and He is near.

18:19.602 --> 18:23.026
Third, we cry out, oh Lord, keep your promise, okay?

18:23.266 --> 18:24.668
Oh Lord, keep your promise.

18:25.389 --> 18:32.258
And their rituals and sacrifices of the Old Testament are sometimes, or maybe oftentimes, if we're honest, difficult for us to comprehend and understand.

18:33.099 --> 18:36.424
They're foreign and strange to our modern ways.

18:36.504 --> 18:41.150
They're bloody and they're violent and they can seem antiquated and barbaric.

18:42.432 --> 18:46.277
But what the Psalmist has in mind here is a confirmation of God's promise.

18:46.658 --> 18:52.626
Here there is an appeal to the covenant that promise or that bond which God makes with the Israelites.

18:53.378 --> 19:02.450
that the language here in verse three, to regard with favor your burnt sacrifices, literally says, set a flame or to make them ashen.

19:02.930 --> 19:08.318
As if to say, God, send down fire from heaven to show that you are pleased with my king's worship.

19:10.581 --> 19:18.891
What's so interesting about this passage is that in the midst of preparing for battle, the people and the king are concerned with the right worship, or worshiping God as he commanded.

19:18.931 --> 19:20.914
This is what we see also in the book of Joshua.

19:21.570 --> 19:29.858
For they knew that success in the battlefield began not with the strength of their men, but with their love for the Lord and their covenant fidelity.

19:31.479 --> 19:33.281
And what a lesson for you and for me as well.

19:33.321 --> 19:43.271
When we feel so busy and overwhelmed, especially to the point where our worshiping together or our private devotion suffers, we've lost the centrality of God's promises and purposes in our lives.

19:44.332 --> 19:50.898
Rather worldly distractions or days of trial and suffering, they can tend to choke out our sense of urgency before the Lord.

19:52.514 --> 20:00.446
Maybe you've been laid off or a loved one has been sick or maybe more responsibility has been given to you and you're struggling with keeping up.

20:00.486 --> 20:04.032
Maybe things are tense at home with your spouse or with your children.

20:04.072 --> 20:09.040
There are days when our earthly troubles seem to eclipse the grand promises of God.

20:10.582 --> 20:15.189
The example here, I think, is that the Lord and His promises are central to your daily life.

20:16.291 --> 20:20.978
Whether in feast or in fallow, we cannot forsake these promises.

20:21.794 --> 20:26.719
In fact, it's Jesus himself who reveals to us what it means to trust completely in God.

20:27.941 --> 20:33.627
He who lived not by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds from the mouth of the Father.

20:34.708 --> 20:39.533
He who would utter the words, not my will, but yours of Father.

20:41.075 --> 20:49.684
He would regularly retreat to the wilderness to pray, he who with tears of blood entrust himself to the Father in the garden of Gethsemane.

20:50.525 --> 20:51.666
Right, surely it's Christ.

20:52.034 --> 20:57.162
who patterns for us and reveals to us what it means to trust in God.

20:58.945 --> 21:09.801
And as the Israelite looked to the altar, to see God's pleasure and surety of his promises, to make those sacrifices ashen, to show forth his covenant love and promise.

21:10.762 --> 21:12.285
So you and I, we look to the cross.

21:13.667 --> 21:15.730
We have the prophetic word more fully confirmed.

21:15.842 --> 21:21.751
In Christ, the promises fulfilled in His finished work, and we should have no doubt that the Lord will keep His promises.

21:21.811 --> 21:25.897
And so, beloved, we cry out, Lord, keep your promises.

21:27.960 --> 21:35.871
Lastly, we cry out, Lord protect us, Lord be near, Lord keep your promises, but we cry out, Lord, bless others.

21:37.934 --> 21:43.122
And verses four and five were reminded not only of whom, but a two whom, but four whom we pray.

21:44.130 --> 21:47.795
We cry out, we appeal to the Lord on behalf of the righteous king.

21:47.835 --> 21:54.485
And we ask the Lord might protect that he might be present and might find the sacrifices acceptable of the king.

21:55.106 --> 22:00.874
Right here, the words of David, he says, may he grant you your heart's desire and fulfill all your plans.

22:01.294 --> 22:03.738
May we shout for joy over your salvation.

22:03.798 --> 22:05.941
And in the name of our God, set up our banners.

22:06.241 --> 22:09.586
May the Lord fulfill all your petitions.

22:11.394 --> 22:14.499
Note that this king is worthy of the prayers of his people.

22:15.400 --> 22:18.044
His desires are holy and right.

22:19.106 --> 22:26.056
For the people with confidence that they can pray that the Lord fulfill his heart's desires and plans.

22:27.538 --> 22:37.874
For king preparing for battle, that his actions might be just, that they not be greedy or vindictive, that he not seek vain glory, but seek the will of the Lord in all things.

22:38.594 --> 22:42.139
The king is one for whom the people want to see spared in battle.

22:43.120 --> 22:52.011
He's not an individual that the people are secretly praying in their hearts, hoping doesn't make it back from the battlefield to take a stray arrow.

22:53.193 --> 23:00.322
He is one in whom the people place their trust in his petitions or his prayers that his will is to be done and enacted.

23:01.844 --> 23:06.930
And on some level, I want you to see that there is an instruction here in the Psalm to pray for the people in power and authority.

23:08.034 --> 23:12.079
There was a call to lift up the righteous one in our midst and to trust in him.

23:12.759 --> 23:18.145
The larger catechism plots our positions of living and how we relate to one another.

23:19.006 --> 23:24.052
We all bear different relations to one another as superiors or equals or inferiors.

23:24.833 --> 23:32.882
And this again, depending on how we relate to one another, we all have some sense or semblance of authority over others and some more than others.

23:34.063 --> 23:36.466
And it is here that we must ask a difficult question

23:36.802 --> 23:42.207
But I think especially as we relate to one another, especially with authority, can this song be prayed of us?

23:43.168 --> 23:46.351
Can others pray that our petitions be granted before the Lord?

23:47.092 --> 23:51.997
Can others pray that the Lord would fulfill our heart's desires and fulfill all our plans?

23:53.058 --> 23:57.362
Might it be that others would shout for joy, literally singing a song over our salvation?

23:57.422 --> 24:01.967
You know, if you're a husband, can your wife pray this of you?

24:02.907 --> 24:05.490
If you're a parent, can your children pray this of you?

24:06.018 --> 24:09.983
If you're an older brother or sister, can your younger siblings pray this of you?

24:10.023 --> 24:13.628
If you're an employer, can your employees pray this of you?

24:14.929 --> 24:19.635
If you're an elder or deacon, can the church pray this of you, of me?

24:19.655 --> 24:28.226
You know, we should see in this a call to pursue the Lord and to listen to Him and obey His commands.

24:29.288 --> 24:31.250
But also we should see here the grace of God.

24:31.906 --> 24:35.791
that Jesus Christ is the greatest fulfillment of this king, we so desire.

24:36.252 --> 24:42.781
One to whom we need not pray these things or for whom we need not pray these things, but rather he prays them for us.

24:44.023 --> 24:46.526
Do you see how Jesus is the greatest fulfillment of this call?

24:46.566 --> 24:48.489
We trust in his desires.

24:49.190 --> 24:52.715
We sing every Sunday over the salvation of him from the grave.

24:53.776 --> 25:00.626
And we know and find great assurance that his prayers are prayed on our behalf for our good and in every circumstance.

25:01.378 --> 25:16.643
We need not pray for Jesus in the way that Israelite might pray for David, interceding, nor how you and I might pray for presidents or legislators, but beloved, what a glorious thought it is that Jesus prays for you and for me.

25:16.683 --> 25:28.562
And the true beauty of this Psalm is that Jesus is the greater king who protects you, is with you, keeps his promises, and is the great blessing of others, the image of God's love for you.

25:34.082 --> 25:43.232
Don Cook is a Marine Corps veteran who had been working at Barrett, a firearms manufacturer and supplier for the US military.

25:44.713 --> 25:53.963
He did so for about 17 years and he was interviewed by National Geographic where he recounts the most interesting call he ever received as a customer service rep.

25:55.265 --> 26:00.370
He picked up the phone one day to the sounds of a firefight on the other end.

26:01.346 --> 26:07.292
Apparently a group of Marines were in the field and under fire and they had accidentally damaged the rifle the day before.

26:08.253 --> 26:08.953
And so what did they do?

26:09.354 --> 26:20.364
Well, somehow they got a hold of Barrett's customer service phone number and they called and he picked up and he walked them through infield repair and within 30 seconds they were back in the fight.

26:21.405 --> 26:22.927
I'm talking about customer service, right?

26:25.149 --> 26:30.834
Well, what this song teaches us is that we have such access to the father through prayer

26:31.458 --> 26:35.422
that when we cry out that the Lord hears and he answers.

26:36.523 --> 27:00.306
And so Christians take heart that when you pray to God, you pray to the one who is there and the one who invites you to pray, who welcomes you to pray, who commands you to pray and know that he will always protect you, that he will always be near to you, that he will always keep your promises and that he will indeed bless those around you.

27:01.218 --> 27:04.422
Let's pray together, would you pray with me?

27:04.442 --> 27:15.257
Father, thank you, O Lord, that you would so give us assurance and that you would so grant us peace, O Lord, to know that you are never far.

27:16.819 --> 27:23.969
And Lord, that you do invite us to pray and that you do so command us, that we might rest and lean upon you.

27:23.989 --> 27:27.634
But Father, might it be that we would dwell

27:28.130 --> 27:41.751
in and with you, O Lord, I know such safety is being in that high tower, being in your hands from which nothing can snatch us, not Satan himself, not sin, not death."

27:43.434 --> 27:51.226
That's why we asked that you would stoke the flames of desire in our hearts, O Lord, to seek your face in prayer.

27:52.568 --> 27:56.114
It might be that you would grant us all comfort and that you would grant us all peace

27:56.802 --> 28:00.287
the Lord to know that you hear, and you do far more abundantly than we can ask or think.

28:02.149 --> 28:07.316
So, God, we pray that you would fill our hearts now with faith, with trust, and bring us to you.

28:08.358 --> 28:09.840
We ask these things in Jesus' name.

28:10.420 --> 28:10.721
Amen.

28:11.682 --> 28:14.085
Let's stand together as we're able and sing our hand of trust.

28:14.126 --> 28:15.968
How sweet the name of Jesus sounds.

